Course.Title: PRINCIPLES OF ACCOUNTING I
Course.Description: This course is an introduction to accounting concepts and principles used in the preparation of financial reports for proprietorships, partnerships, and corporations. The generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) that are used in this process will be explained and incorporated into all of the instruction. It involves the application of the techniques of using debits and credits, the preparation and analysis of the trial balances (both unadjusted and adjusted), making adjusting entries and assessing the effectiveness of the internal control system of an entity. The student will continuously be exposed to the preparation and analysis of the basic financial statements showing students how to evaluate an entity's performance, and how outside parties use financial statements to make various decisions on those statements.

The student will continuously be exposed to the preparation and analysis of the basic financial statements showing students how to evaluate an entity's performance, and how outside parties use financial statements to make various decisions on those statements.

Course.Title: PRINCIPLES OF ACCOUNTING II
Course.Description: Principles of Accounting II is a continuation of the topics covered in Principles of Accounting 1. It builds on the skills, tools and techniques developed and utilized for measuring and analyzing a company's operating and financing activities. The analysis and interpretation of financial statements will be emphasized. Accounting for partnerships and corporations' equities will be introduced. Special issues in connection with the accounting for investments and liabilities and the usefulness of the statement of cash flows will be addressed. This course will also focus on some of the tools and techniques used in managerial accounting.
